show_title: GM Farcaster ep166 Wednesday October 9, 2024 with guest cohosts @christin and @cameron
text:
Channels update

1. It was a big change, but overall I think sentiment is net positive across a good chunk of the network

2. The most common frustrations:
a. losing access to a favorite channel, esp. if you had a streak in it
b. seeing your reply "below the fold"
c. older casts in channels disappearing from personal profiles
d. many channels not having clear instructions for joining

So what we're doing this week

3. Continue to talk to users (mostly me) and pay attention to feedback

4. We're considering some tweaks to how above / below the fold works for non-members, esp. if the original caster is following someone. We won't make any sudden changes here, fwiw

5. Strongly considering adding back older casts in channels to profiles (with a label on the cast). The data is untouched at the protocol level, just hidden on Warpcast right now.

6. Continue to get feedback from channel owners / mods / users / developers on making request to join a channel a primitive similar to invites. Again, no sudden changes.

show_title: GM Farcaster ep166 Wednesday October 9, 2024 with guest cohosts @christin and @cameron
text:
Channel update summary

Since this cast yesterday, we've already:
1. Brought older channel casts back to user profiles
2. Added a dedicated channels tab in notifications to everyone
3. Proposed an iteration for how replies work to be more inclusive

Still on our radar:
4. Make it easier for people to request to join a channel, leveraging the growing set of tools built by developers; channel owners can decide how they want to do it
5. Make it easier to invite people to your channel from a reply / DC / profile
6. What to do with abandoned channels

show_title: GM Farcaster ep166 Wednesday October 9, 2024 with guest cohosts @christin and @cameron
text:
Maybe to help others.... today I setup @modbot in /purple to use our Purple NFT as the Channel Membership. But then I kicked everyone out of the channel because they were just auto-assigned to the channel and I wanted to make sure only Purple members were in the channels. 

Well it turns out, kicking someone out of the channel bans them, so I actually banned most of our membership! Big thanks to @haole who helped us unban everyone and now its working correctly. 

tldr; don't be me! If you remove someone from a channel modbot sees that as a ban (makes sense in retrospect)

show_title: GM Farcaster ep166 Wednesday October 9, 2024 with guest cohosts @christin and @cameron
GM Farcaster ep166 Wednesday October 9, 2024 with guest cohosts @christin and @cameron
text:
I'm wondering how new Farcaster users will get into channels.

How can they grow and be seen if they haven't been invited to certain channels because they're completely new here?

Any thoughts/tips? Would casting without a channel be powerful enough to help them grow? It could be a great option if it worked that way 
Should they DM channel owners and moderators to request an invite? 

I'm asking because I'm constantly trying to onboard new people by encouraging them to join the /london channel here

show_title: GM Farcaster ep166 Wednesday October 9, 2024 with guest cohosts @christin and @cameron
text: Just because you send ‘em, doesn’t mean we read ‘em

show_title: GM Farcaster ep166 Wednesday October 9, 2024 with guest cohosts @christin and @cameron
text:
In most cases, I agree with this.

General topic channels don't work well in the new model. They were built an era of channels as hashtags.

There will be some exceptions, but will require a lot of work from the channel owner and moderators to make sure a large channel becomes and stays a community.

cast.text: I unfollowed all the huge channels, they don't make sense to me anymore. People should just broadcast into the Main feed and have more thoughtful discussions in channels.

show_title: GM Farcaster ep166 Wednesday October 9, 2024 with guest cohosts @christin and @cameron
text:
What are we missing?

Also worth pointing out that the next "big" project is onboarding directly to a channel.

Rough idea: you can invite someone to Farcaster and when they sign up, they immediately join your channel(s) and their initial home feed is weighted toward your channels and people you interact with a lot. 

Should help solve having a group of people to interact with on Day 1 without worrying about not having access to channels and/or spam labeling.

show_title: GM Farcaster ep166 Wednesday October 9, 2024 with guest cohosts @christin and @cameron
text:
One thing I was wrong about over the last few years: sign up costs would dramatically reduce spam. 

Turns out spam is a top 3 problem (aside from retention and infrastructure scaling) to solve for when building a permissionless decentralized social networking protocol.

Spammers are willing to pay for sign ups at prices that normal users aren't.

Spam is also relative: what's spammy for one person is not for another.

Corollary: when you talk to developers building on Farcaster, spam is a top of mind issue whereas users giving product feedback but not actively building in the ecosystem tend to think this isn't that big an issue / not that hard a problem to solve. 

Also a good proxy for the quality of first principles thinking when suggesting "why don't you just do this?" if you haven't considered how would spammers abuse this and what's the solution.
